data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

**What happened:** In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions mean `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` overload **cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree**, so it throws at runtime when the expression is compiled/interpreted.

**How to fix:** Force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>`:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9) — breaks on .NET 10
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.Contains(num);

// After — explicitly target Enumerable.Contains
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Alternative: use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Alternative: call Enumerable.Contains directly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three options prevent the compiler from choosing the `Span`-based overload, keeping the expression tree valid.
